<subSubSection id="C32ADAB5FFE20F46F853FA4CC566F8D6" pageId="16" pageNumber="199" type="description">
<paragraph id="8B8F893EFFE20F46F853FA4CC664F9C0" blockId="16.[1987,2582,1213,1635]" pageId="16" pageNumber="199">
<emphasis id="B944552CFFE20F46F853FA4CC4CBF9B7" bold="true" box="[1987,2238,1523,1556]" pageId="16" pageNumber="199">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head—body 63-77 mm, tail 80-86 mm, hindfoot 20-20 mm. No specific data are available for body weight.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8F893EFFE20F46FACEF9D7C566F8D6" blockId="16.[1372,2580,1640,2263]" pageId="16" pageNumber="199">Vernay’s African Climbing Mouse is small, with very long prehensile tail. Tail is bicolored, darker above and paler below. Fur is long, soft, and brown or reddish-brown dorsally and grayish ventrally. Base of each hair is dark gray. Black line runs mid-dorsally from mid-back to base oftail. Earsare relatively large and rounded. Limbs are adapted for climbing. Second to fourth digits of forelimbs have elongated claws, and first and fifth digits are greatly reduced. Hindlimb has second to fourth digits elongated, fifth digit long and opposable with a claw, and first digit greatly reduced.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
